I am experienced in making small-scale literal translations in many languages.
These ten Basho (Hashiyou) haiku translations are my first in Japanese,
with a few original romaji (romashi) divisions:


1) Old Pond

huru ike ya
ka wasu tohi komu
misu no oto

Jilted - go or
Mosquito evading; flying-crowding,
Mistake of sound


2) Summer Grasses

natsu kusa ya
tsuwa mono tomo a
yume no ato

Summer-salvation, or
Bowl-person: friend, a
Dream of after


3) Autumn Evening

kare eta ni
kara su no to mari keri
aki no kure

Him as poor;
Mosquitos of staying-reason. Kicking
Free space of giving.


4) Journey/Death Poem

tahi ni yan te
yume wa kare no wo
kake me uru

Travel as familiar-person-hand -
Dreaming returning of the
Fragment-eye to sell


5) Cicada's Voice

shisu kesa ya
iwa ni shimiiru
semi no koe

Stillness, or
Sink down as a boulder,
A locust of voice


6) Winter Rain

nosarashi wo
kokora ni kikamu
shi ure kana

Weather-beaten, the
Mind as; to feel like
In ripeness. Alas.


7) Morning Glory

asa ao ni
ware wa meshi kuu
otoku kana

Morning ao, as
Broken piece return - meal eat;
Man. Alas.


8) Cherry Blossoms

ki ni hurete
hiki mo itowanu
sakura kana

Tree as: touch;
Pull back. Also: willingly;
Decoy. Alas.


9) Spring Passing

yuku haru ya
tori naki uwo no
me ha namita

To move towards; to stretch - or:
Bird-less, burn incense. Of
Me, is tears.


10) First Winter Rain

hatsu shi ure
saru mo komino o
hoshi e nari

First time in ripeness:
Monkey. Also: garbage collection day. Male!
Star, wisdom? Style.


